No, not really. I'm comparing two different cases in which changes were made to the ground rules that affected people already on the list. In the first case, the rule was implemented fairly, so that it only effected new additions and not those already on the list. In the second case it was implemented dictatorially, with everyone on the list told, in essence, &quot;deal with it&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;By the definition of the new rule, it MUST be retroactive.&quot;<br>
<br>
Draw a line across the list. Next to it write &quot;no changing places below this line&quot;. Problem solved.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your situation is actually one that I wish they could figure out a way to accomodate without abuse&quot;.<br>
<br>
Maybe it's just me, but I haven't seen any abuse. What's the big terror here?<br>
<br>
